
Intro to Docker stuff

Whats the deal with Containers?
Basically we used to have the "it works on my machine" nightmare. One person has java 8, other has java 17... everything breaks. 

1. The Apartment Cloud (aka Virtualization / VMs)
Think of a huge building where every apartment has its own everything. Own walls, own pipes, own rules. 
- You want to run a small app? You gotta bring a whole Operating System (Guest OS) with it. 
- It’s too heavy and takes forever to boot up.
- Uses a Hypervisor to manage these "apartments".

2. The Modern Way (Containerization)
Now imagine sharing the base building but having your own furniture and stuff.
- Containers share the Host OS Kernel.
- No need to carry a whole OS for every app.
- Super fast (boots in seconds).

Why use it?
It wraps everything (code, libs, tools) into one box. If it works in the container on my laptop, it’ll work on the server. Period.

Important Word: Immutability.
Basically means: once you build it, you don't touch it. If you need a change, just build a new version. Don't fix it while it's running.

Command basic:
- docker --version (just checking if its there)
- docker info (shows if any containers are running, memory stuff etc.)

*Teacher mentioned: Docker is like a standardized shipping container for code.* 
*Handy alt: Podman (mostly same as docker but handles rootless stuff better).*
